\begin_layout Standard
So one piece of useless baggage is this.
 In a conventional fiber bundle,
 the base space is distinguished:
 it carries a topology,
 and a section is a function into the fibers.
 Flipping it on it's side is tricky:
 if one mentally imagines a *single* fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 then there is no map (no function) from a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in F$
\end_inset

 to all of the points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

 of the base–space 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 where the fiber might be valued as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Its just not a function,
 and there's no way to cure this,
 at least,
 if one thinks of a *single* fiber.
 Yes,
 locally,
 a fiber bundle looks like the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times F$
\end_inset

,
 but the gluing of the fibers makes use of the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and not on 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is distinguished.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So how do I turn 
\begin_inset Formula $E=B\times F$
\end_inset

 on its side?
 Well,
 for starters,
 the fundamental objects need to be the sections 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and not the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 And the sections need to be space–like,
 I guess,
 so I want to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 retaining a time coordinate but having the space coordinate be implicit.
 All this drives to the Hamiltonian picture.
 Next,
 if this is actually,
 really,
 truly an operator–valued fiber bundle,
 then I have to ask what the horizontal and vertical subspaces are,
 and what the connection is.
 This has to be a connection on an inf–dimensional fiber,
 and the fiber is explicitly the Weyl algebra.
\end_layout

