 and insofar as these can be presumed to somehow be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

independent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 then they do span a space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 And this space can be taken to be a fiber,
 and the coordinates on each fiber can be varied by applying a varying symplectic 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 obeying the loose constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{T}JM=J$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset

).
 But doing this appears to be pointless,
 as there is no independent dynamics for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 – it really is just a coordinate transformation and nothing more.
 There was a whisper of a hope that one of the forms might 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

look like something
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
 have some familiar form,
 and thus suggesting some alternative interpretation,
 but I see nothing of that sort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What was that whisper?
 Well,
 that something Bogoliubov–y would be recognizable here.
 But Bogoliubov works with the creation/annihilation operators,
 which is not what we have here.
 So lets now return to that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process is to then copy out another handful of formulas from B&D.
 The main one is this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a\left(k\right),a^{\dagger}\left(k^{\prime}\right)\right]=\delta^{3}\left(\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{k}^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset

On the RHS are 3-vectors,
 the wave–vectors.
 On the LHS are 4-vectors,
 but the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}$
\end_inset

 is taken to be on–shell,
 so fixed by the spatial 3-vector.
 The footnote on page 28 provides a way of writing the on–shell condition in a Lorentz–invariant way,
 which requires the use of a positive–energy condition using the Heaviside func 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(k_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earlier,
 we'd taken the liberty of writing
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\left(k\right)=ie_{p}\left(k\right)+\omega_{k}e_{q}\left(k\right)
\]

\end_inset

and then making use of the interpretation that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{q}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]\qquad e_{p}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

one can again imagine a reparameterization of a symplectic 
\begin_inset Formula $M\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 that varies by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 At the current state of play,
 this again seems pointless.
 Still,
 lets continue.
 B&D give us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H & =\frac{1}{2}\int d^{3}k\;\omega_{k}\left[a^{\dagger}\left(k\right)a\left(k\right)+a\left(k\right)a^{\dagger}\left(k\right)\right]\\
\mathbf{P} & =\frac{1}{2}\int d^{3}k\;\mathbf{k}\left[a^{\dagger}\left(k\right)a\left(k\right)+a\left(k\right)a^{\dagger}\left(k\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We want to work backwards from here:
 B&D takes 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 to be (infinite–dimensional) operators acting on the Hilbert space spanned by the harmonic oscillator basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and so of course the product is just the plain old operator product.
 But we do not yet want to assume this mapping,
 and go back one step earlier,
 and use the explicit tensor product.
 Doing this gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a^{\dagger}\otimes a+a\otimes a^{\dagger} & =\left(\omega e_{q}-ie_{p}\right)\otimes\left(\omega e_{q}+ie_{p}\right)+\left(\omega e_{q}+ie_{p}\right)\otimes\left(\omega e_{q}-ie_{p}\right)\\
 & =2\left[\omega^{2}e_{q}\otimes e_{q}+e_{p}\otimes e_{p}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so this is a circle (ellipse,
 whatever.) I guess we are going round in circles.
 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{2}=\mathbf{k}^{2}+m^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can verify the tensorial anti–commutator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\otimes a^{\dagger}-a^{\dagger}\otimes a & =2i\omega\left[e_{p}\otimes e_{q}-e_{q}\otimes e_{p}\right]\\
 & =-2i\omega
\end{align*}

\end_inset

because the Clifford algebra was generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\otimes e_{p}-e_{p}\otimes e_{q}=1$
\end_inset

 although I can see my notation above has not been entirely consistent.
 The point here is that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{\dagger}\otimes a+a\otimes a^{\dagger}=2a\otimes a^{\dagger}+2i\omega
\]

\end_inset

Ah frick–n–frack,
 my inconsistent notation has screwed things up,
 and I'm too lazy to go and fix it.
 The claim that I wanted to make is a very old one:
 that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 comes from the commutator,
 i.e.
 it is an in–built consequence of the Clifford algebra,
 and is not some wonky side–effect arising from the Hermite–polynomial representation.
 That is,
 this zero–point energy will be there no matter what representation is used for these operators (including,
 for example,
 the Mumford theta representation.
 It's a curious representation,
 but it does not rescue us from this prior algebraic consequence.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I've spent several days very carefully picking apart very basic concepts,
 and for what?
 I suppose that perhaps I've closed some imagined loopholes that my flighty imagination would have otherwise left open.
 That's lemonade,
 right?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
23 March 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In between the above,
 I'm reading NYRB.
 A variety of half–finished thoughts are begging for verbal expression.
 In the meanwhile,
 I'm idling and killing time,
 wandering down some less intellectually challenging routes,
 in this case,
 reading more of B&D.
 I first read it when I was 20,
 senior year of college,
 going into first year of grad school,
 so reading it is going down memory lane – a vaguely pleasant if idle journey through old corridors.
 This time,
 I'm focusing more on reading the tea leaves – the disclaimers,
 if's,
 and and buts,
 casting doubts on the overall validity of the theory.
 The concerns are valid,
 technically speaking,
 but no longer seem so operative.
 Some of the infinities can be avoided by working with wave–packets,
 i.e.
 finite–sized instrumentation,
 corresponding to that which is physically realizable and measurable.
 Some can be mathematically formalized in acceptable ways,
 e.g the compactly–generated topology.
 One could get lost in asking how some of these divergent quantities 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

really behave
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 when computed using such more precise mathematical techniques,
 but my gut intuition is that nothing particularly surprising or unexpected happens there – it's not a place to go hunting.
 The one infinity that does pique my interest,
 the one that I don't understand,
 is the zero–point energy,
 and this is because it is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 – in Hawking and Unruh radiation,
 and of course in the Lamb shift.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

See Chapter 4
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 say the notes.
 I guess I will need to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The book also raises questions of validity at smaller length scales.
 It was written before the rise of QCD,
 so maybe the authors were thinking of that,
 rather than of Planck–scale phenomena.
 So far,
 I've not seen the words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Planck–scale
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in that text.
 Why am I writing this?
 Because I find these expressions of uncertainty and doubt entertaining and amusing.
 There's a certain charm to it.
 It's like – 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we worked out this incredibly complicated theory,
 and it seems to be right,
 and yet here is where the frontier lies.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The unknown.
 NYRB April 9,
 2026 has an article:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Interminable Ignorance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 Robert Pogue Harrison,
 which lights up my mind,
 and I want to write a commentary on that.
 And maybe I will,
 later.
 But for just right now,
 I'm continuing with B&D because that seems both easier,
 and more productive.
 I feel that I learn more poking at physics,
 than I do hand–wringing and developing an amateur philosophy of mind,
 a la St.
 Augustine or Freud.
 Two nights ago,
 watched the movie 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Night of the Iguanas
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 based on a Tennessee Williams play.
 Williams is a master of capturing the feeling of angst,
 of being at the end of one's rope,
 at the very precipice of a nervous breakdown.
 This is somehow co–leagued with the question of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what's it all about?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that seems to eat at the soul of most people,
 even if usually subdued and subconscious.
 And it goes hand in hand with my earlier ruminations:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

why is everyone crazy,
 but me?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is paired with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the fluidity and expanse of my own character and soul gives me the ability to empathize with anyone in any situation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there,
 but for the grace of God,
 go I
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 So perhaps everyone is crazy,
 because they are like me,
 and I am crazy,
 perhaps like some character in a Tennessee Williams play,
 or well,
 some Freudian character.
 In my dreams last night,
 in a fit of frustration,
 I feigned an accident and stepped on my sister's laptop,
 breaking it.
 It was angry because Apple products are pieces of shit,
 embodied enshittification in an operating system.
 This dream was repulsive to me,
 angst–ridden and unpleasant.
 Cory Doctorow's frustration with enshitification does not (cannot?) rise to the level of Tennessee Williams angst.
 Oh,
 by the,
 by late mornings,
 my dreams turned to a sexually explicit form.
 Entirely pleasant.
 Unfortunately,
 Freud would be disappointed,
 as the aura of pleasure was not tangled into any negative emotion or impulse.
 See,
 this is what I mean:
 everyone is crazy,
 except me.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Speaking of:
 that NYRB issue also reviews Firesign Theatre.
 I'm of course smack–dab center of the demographic,
 having nearly memorized entire sides of their record albums.
 The review of the article does point out,
 though,
 that the material is a bit thin.
 And this got me to thinking:
 what does 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mean,
 in this context?
 If you were to take some great novel,
 and turn it into a movie,
 you only avoid threadbare thinness by spending ten minutes on each page,
 articulating the emotional,
 psychological,
 philosophical ruminations of the author – the ingredients that make the book 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

great
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to begin with,
 as opposed to some goof–ball mostly empty TV series.
 And at ten minutes per page times 400 pages:
 that's sixty hours of film–making.
 Entirely impossible.
 The great novelist is reaching for something sublime and ineffable,
 necessarily having to anchor it on a story/plot.
 Firesign Theatre only had 9 albums of 40 minutes to work with.
 The material is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 only because it avoids the personal:
 the grand hopes and dreams and loves of the soul,
 the things that stir passion.
 Instead,
 the topic is entirely different:
 the enshittification of society.
 Firesign Theatre creates sound–scapes,
 not literary text or poetry.
 They tackle themes not of the individual,
 but of society,
 and society and culture do not stir with passion and desire;
 instead its a stream of corporate non–sense and the proclamations of self–important egos pronouncing garbage and bullshit on the front pages of newspapers across America.
 It is this spew of bullshit that the Firesign Theatre attacks.
 The material is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 only because the culture and society that was forged via mass media is itself thin,
 weak,
 empty and depressingly stupid when it's not outright toxic.
 We live in a civilizational crisis,
 epitomized by Trump,
 because the machinery that amplifies society appears to amplify the corrupt and the putrid more than the wholesome and the healthy.
 Society itself seems on the verge of a Tennessee–Williams–esque nervous breakdown.
 But this is hard to dramatize,
 because society is to some large degree invisible.
 The critiques that are turned into movies are almost uniformly apocalyptic,
 from the Handmaid's Tale to 1984.
 Horror stories.
 The ones that are uplifiting,
 say,
 the Sound of Music,
 are marginally schmaltzy.
 What's left is Firesign Theatre:
 comedy music.
 Frank Zappa.
 And comedy is,
 well,
 the antithesis of heft.
 There's no drama without tragedy.
 We empathize only with others like ourselves,
 other humans.
 On occasion,
 we can empathize with our mammalian pets.
 But to have some natural,
 instinctive empathy for society and culture?
 May as well try to empathize with space aliens from Atlantis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whatever.
 So there.
 I have to read some B&D now.
 Or maybe first to make coffee.
 Or something.
 See.
 Writing the above non–sense is just personal hand–wringing,
 angst.
 It does no particular good,
 does not seem to do any particular good.
 I reach for some ineffable thing,
 but my contacts with the ineffable – well,
 it comes through mathematics.
 I think that same issue of NYRB has a review of some of Lockhart's work.
 That review is ...
 underwhelming and disappointing.
 But I did like the comment about the pure sublime abstractness of it all,
 and the uselessness.
 And that seems to be the ultimate critique of all human activity:
 almost all of it is useless.
 We fuck around cause it's fun.
 We find out cause is inevitable within our light–cone.
 OK,
 really,
 I have to stop.
 I'm not getting any closer,
 here.
